<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-01-29T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-01-29T04:00:00-05:00" n="604" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d604">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/2638: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Tenney</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-01-29T17:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">January
                                            29, 1920—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received January
                                    29—11:20 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>29. Referring to Legation’s telegram January 27, 5 p.m. The Japanese
                                Minister proposes that the four Legations concerned instruct the
                                four banks concerned to make certain advances to the Chinese
                                Government to enable it to tide over the Chinese New Year <pb facs="0722" n="624" xml:id="pg_624"/> settlement day, such
                                advances to be deducted 5,000,000 pounds loan when arranged. Please
                                telegraph instructions without delay.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Tenney</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>